<h1><strong>Overview</strong></h1>

<p>Help us quickly identify cases of pneumonia in children. Our goal is to help flag serious cases, quickly identify healthy cases, and act as a diagnostic aid for doctors.</p>
<hr>

<h1><strong>Steps</strong></h1>

<ol>
	<li>Examine the image.</li>
	<li>If there are <strong>pneumonia symptoms</strong> in the image, check the appropriate box ('Yes', 'No', or 'Unknown').</li>
</ol>
<hr>

<h1><strong>Rules Tips</strong></h1>

<p><strong>Rules:</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li>Only look for <strong>p</strong><strong>neumonia</strong> symptoms</li>
	<li>Pneumonia symptoms must be <strong>visible</strong> in heart, lungs (ribs), and/or diaphragm</li>
	<li>Images <strong>missing areas</strong> of heart, lungs (ribs), and/or diaphragm must be checked as 'Unknown'.</li>
	<li>Images with <strong>any unidentifiable objects</strong> in heart, lungs (ribs), and/or diaphragm must be deemed 'Unknown'.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Tips</strong>:</p>

<ul>
	<li>A <strong>normal</strong>, healthy image (below) depicting clear lungs without any areas of abnormal cloudiness/opacity; there may be structured, web-like vasculature in the lungs but otherwise that area should be clear. In healthy images, you are also more likely to see a diaphragm shadow.</li>
</ul>

<p><img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/crowdflower-make-cloud/images%2F1583096818479-healthy-example.png" class="fr-fic fr-dii" style="width: 853px;"></p>

<ul>
	<li>A <strong>pneumonia</strong> image (below) may include a few things: areas of cloudiness/opacity in several concentrated areas or one large area. You may also see a general pattern of opacity that obscures the structure of the lungs, heart and diaphragm.</li>
</ul>

<p><img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/crowdflower-make-cloud/images%2F1583096803779-pneumonia-examples.png" class="fr-fic fr-dii">
	<br>
</p>
<hr>

